1
00:00:01,780 --> 00:00:10,940
Amen. Thank you, worship team. Good morning. Welcome. It is good to be back with you. I trust you had fun with my colleague, Bob Orr, last week.

2
00:00:11,580 --> 00:00:18,840
If you were not here, we had a little switcheroo. I got a chance to preach in Santa Ana, and he got a chance to share here.

3
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:27,560
And it was, I think, fun for both of us. And we met afterwards for lunch, swapped stories, and you were all very gracious and loving to him.

4
00:00:27,560 --> 00:00:29,640
and likewise down in Santa Ana.

5
00:00:29,800 --> 00:00:32,800
So we had a good time sharing each other's churches

6
00:00:32,800 --> 00:00:34,340
and encouraging the people.

7
00:00:34,760 --> 00:00:36,920
I also just want to say up front

8
00:00:36,920 --> 00:00:40,520
that a wonderful thing has happened in our family this week.

9
00:00:42,700 --> 00:00:45,260
My youngest has decided to follow Jesus.

10
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:49,920
And I want to thank you as a body.

11
00:00:50,460 --> 00:00:52,980
I want to thank you especially Carmen Huipe

12
00:00:52,980 --> 00:00:55,340
and others in our children's department

13
00:00:55,340 --> 00:00:59,300
who have been plowing that soil

14
00:00:59,300 --> 00:01:03,280
and I walked by his bedroom and mommy was there talking with him

15
00:01:03,280 --> 00:01:07,380
and I heard this conversation and he blessed my heart and I realized

16
00:01:07,380 --> 00:01:11,300
that with the ministry of our children's ministry here, God is doing

17
00:01:11,300 --> 00:01:15,380
a great work and so now both of my sons, because of your faithfulness

18
00:01:15,380 --> 00:01:19,260
in ministering to my children, are now followers of the Lord

19
00:01:19,260 --> 00:01:23,520
Jesus Christ. And that's what it's all about and I couldn't be happier.

20
00:01:26,420 --> 00:01:29,320
So my encouragement to you in children's and youth

21
00:01:29,320 --> 00:01:36,120
ministry, you do far more than you may ever realize, and I want to thank you and I bless

22
00:01:36,120 --> 00:01:36,700
you for that.

23
00:01:37,970 --> 00:01:39,170
Well, it was a great day.

24
00:01:39,250 --> 00:01:40,030
It's a great day today.

25
00:01:40,130 --> 00:01:42,210
We celebrate a birthday today.

26
00:01:42,910 --> 00:01:46,190
We celebrate a church today.

27
00:01:46,490 --> 00:01:52,800
We celebrate a church born in the heart of God and ignited in the hearts of a small group

28
00:01:52,800 --> 00:02:02,990
of people in this once rural community 110 years ago a community known as fullerton and our church

29
00:02:02,990 --> 00:02:07,410
in that rural community and if you've seen the pictures and they're in this room next door this

30
00:02:07,410 --> 00:02:17,290
little little church with dirt all around a little mission outpost of jesus on this part of the

31
00:02:17,290 --> 00:02:27,340
Southern California plain. Wow. An outpost for Jesus Christ. And 110 years later, that vision

32
00:02:27,340 --> 00:02:34,840
of seeing an outpost for Jesus Christ, that vision continues because the mission continues today.

33
00:02:35,980 --> 00:02:42,660
In fact, our church and any church that proclaims Jesus, for that matter, is today a mission church

34
00:02:42,660 --> 00:02:47,450
in our culture. You see, in the early and the mid

35
00:02:47,450 --> 00:02:51,270
20th century, our church, like many churches in our

36
00:02:51,270 --> 00:02:55,430
community, was a central part of the community.

37
00:02:57,330 --> 00:03:00,170
But yet, at the end of the 20th and the

38
00:03:00,170 --> 00:03:04,350
beginning of the 21st century, which we now live, we can

39
00:03:04,350 --> 00:03:07,730
understand that the spiritual landscape has changed

40
00:03:07,730 --> 00:03:12,600
and that the church is no longer a central part of community life.

41
00:03:13,120 --> 00:03:16,180
It's not that we haven't been faithful to our calling.

42
00:03:16,640 --> 00:03:18,760
Rather, the community has changed.

43
00:03:19,040 --> 00:03:22,220
The spiritual climate has changed.

44
00:03:24,150 --> 00:03:25,370
And we can never go back.

45
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:35,180
But the church of Jesus Christ lives today at the margins of our society.

46
00:03:35,580 --> 00:03:40,440
And we no longer hold that prominent place in the eyes of the community around us.

47
00:03:40,780 --> 00:03:43,680
I find Fullerton to actually be an anomaly.

48
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:52,050
because they still allow me as a pastor to come to various chamber of commerce events

49
00:03:52,050 --> 00:04:00,890
and to give an invocation and I can pray boldly in the name of Jesus and it's still okay.

50
00:04:02,130 --> 00:04:02,470
Amen.

51
00:04:03,770 --> 00:04:05,730
But that may not last forever.

52
00:04:06,210 --> 00:04:12,470
And so when I share that with other colleagues, they are amazed that I can get away with that

53
00:04:12,470 --> 00:04:18,550
Whereas that used to be normative, part of the experience of the community gathering together,

54
00:04:18,970 --> 00:04:25,000
whether for business, for church, whatever, Jesus was held up, but not any longer.

55
00:04:26,400 --> 00:04:30,280
As we are now moving to the margins, I want to encourage you with this.

56
00:04:30,840 --> 00:04:33,760
From the margins, we have a voice.

57
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:38,680
You see, the early church lived in similar circumstances.

58
00:04:39,340 --> 00:04:43,500
The early church did not have the benefits of recognition and prestige.

59
00:04:43,500 --> 00:04:48,320
The early Christians were deemed crazy, a sect.

60
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:53,260
They were even considered, listen, cannibalistic.

61
00:04:54,450 --> 00:04:55,430
Now why would that be?

62
00:04:56,360 --> 00:05:01,760
Well, it was rumored that they ate the body and blood of Jesus at communion.

63
00:05:03,880 --> 00:05:09,660
This weird group of people gathering and drinking blood,

64
00:05:09,780 --> 00:05:14,270
that was the impression of the early church in the early community.

65
00:05:14,270 --> 00:05:18,590
but from the margins the early church had a witness

66
00:05:18,590 --> 00:05:21,790
and their primary witness in the early days

67
00:05:21,790 --> 00:05:23,090
was made credible

68
00:05:23,090 --> 00:05:26,910
when the early Christians took care of the sick

69
00:05:26,910 --> 00:05:28,290
and the dying

70
00:05:28,290 --> 00:05:30,890
when the diseases and the plagues

71
00:05:30,890 --> 00:05:32,610
swept through the community

72
00:05:32,610 --> 00:05:35,310
and took out a quarter to a third of the people

73
00:05:35,310 --> 00:05:36,870
every time it swept through

74
00:05:36,870 --> 00:05:39,670
and you know what happened

75
00:05:39,670 --> 00:05:41,410
who stayed behind

76
00:05:41,410 --> 00:05:44,060
to love the sick and the dying

77
00:05:44,060 --> 00:05:46,030
was the Christians

78
00:05:47,620 --> 00:05:53,080
And that witness of being faithful in the midst of great calamity

79
00:05:53,080 --> 00:05:56,940
gave them a prominence and a rooting in a community.

80
00:05:56,940 --> 00:06:02,860
They were in the margins, but because they were faithful, the church grew.

81
00:06:05,070 --> 00:06:08,070
The faith had depth and real love, and the church grew.

82
00:06:08,930 --> 00:06:11,610
And as the church grew without the benefits of being at the center,

83
00:06:12,150 --> 00:06:14,150
the church has known life at the margins.

84
00:06:14,470 --> 00:06:15,490
We live at the margins.

85
00:06:15,490 --> 00:06:19,930
And I guess I want to say, it's okay to be at the margins.

86
00:06:20,830 --> 00:06:29,320
Because, you know, our forefathers in the faith, foremothers, the Israelites lived much of their life at the margins.

87
00:06:32,210 --> 00:06:38,550
Particularly when God judged the nation of Israel for its disobedience and worship of other gods,

88
00:06:38,910 --> 00:06:42,790
they really went into exile and to live at the margins.

89
00:06:42,790 --> 00:06:49,090
Around the 6th century B.C., they were far-flung and divided.

90
00:06:50,450 --> 00:07:02,650
And when all hope seemed lost, when God seemed distant and quiet and absent, God can bring renewal.

91
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:09,120
I want us to take a look at this text from Isaiah this morning.

92
00:07:09,120 --> 00:07:16,180
When the Jews had been in exile, God seemed removed and gone.

93
00:07:16,780 --> 00:07:18,900
This word came in Isaiah 54.

94
00:07:20,350 --> 00:07:21,410
The first three verses.

95
00:07:21,710 --> 00:07:26,330
Sing, O barren woman, you who never bore a child.

96
00:07:27,010 --> 00:07:29,750
Burst into song and shout for joy.

97
00:07:30,390 --> 00:07:38,330
You who were never in labor because more of the children of the desperate woman than ever who has a husband, says the Lord.

98
00:07:38,730 --> 00:07:41,130
Enlarge the place of your tent.

99
00:07:41,930 --> 00:07:43,930
Stretch your tent curtains wide.

100
00:07:43,930 --> 00:07:45,890
Do not hold back.

101
00:07:47,190 --> 00:07:48,370
Lengthen your cords.

102
00:07:48,990 --> 00:07:50,350
Strengthen your stakes.

103
00:07:51,260 --> 00:07:54,220
For you will spread out to the right and to the left.

104
00:07:54,540 --> 00:07:59,560
Your descendants will dispossess nations and settle in their desolate cities.

105
00:08:02,040 --> 00:08:02,920
It's quite an image.

106
00:08:04,040 --> 00:08:05,540
The image of the barren woman.

107
00:08:05,540 --> 00:08:12,160
In the culture of that time, a barren woman was seen as without God's blessing

108
00:08:12,160 --> 00:08:15,520
and was in a state of continual mourning.

109
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:18,410
And then God breaks in.

110
00:08:19,860 --> 00:08:24,260
Sing, O barren woman, for you're about to have many children.

111
00:08:24,780 --> 00:08:26,360
Enlarge the place of your tent.

112
00:08:26,500 --> 00:08:27,760
Get strong stakes.

113
00:08:28,220 --> 00:08:32,620
Make the cords longer, for you're about to have a big family gathering.

114
00:08:35,320 --> 00:08:37,780
This text in the message, look how it's translated.

115
00:08:38,220 --> 00:08:41,320
Clear lots of ground for your tents.

116
00:08:42,250 --> 00:08:43,670
Make your tents large.

117
00:08:44,250 --> 00:08:45,030
Spread out.

118
00:08:45,730 --> 00:08:47,010
Think big.

119
00:08:47,010 --> 00:08:52,270
an amazing word when God seemed distant

120
00:08:52,270 --> 00:08:56,110
when the people were in exile think big

121
00:08:56,110 --> 00:09:00,980
God is still at work even when God seems to be

122
00:09:00,980 --> 00:09:05,200
absent God is in control do we believe that

123
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:09,180
church that God is in control even when the church

124
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:12,680
is at the margins of the society God is still in control

125
00:09:12,680 --> 00:09:17,800
we're still to be faithful and God can move

126
00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:20,230
and have a voice from the margins.

127
00:09:21,650 --> 00:09:24,750
The church in the U.S. today, I believe,

128
00:09:24,870 --> 00:09:26,790
is in exile from the dominant culture,

129
00:09:26,790 --> 00:09:29,890
and I do not see that trend turning around anytime soon.

130
00:09:30,350 --> 00:09:31,770
But I'm not worried.

131
00:09:32,750 --> 00:09:33,610
I am not worried.

132
00:09:34,700 --> 00:09:37,240
Because it's been said that God still plays dead

133
00:09:37,240 --> 00:09:38,740
to see if we notice.

134
00:09:40,020 --> 00:09:40,960
And here's the point.

135
00:09:41,140 --> 00:09:44,000
When God plays dead, it's the beginning of hope.

136
00:09:45,460 --> 00:09:48,080
When we feel like we're marginalized and on the edge

137
00:09:48,080 --> 00:09:50,200
and where is God and where is our prominence

138
00:09:50,200 --> 00:09:52,780
and where is all the prestige of being the church,

139
00:09:53,240 --> 00:09:55,460
now we can begin to have renewal together.

140
00:09:56,320 --> 00:09:58,900
We may not find the church at the center of the community,

141
00:09:59,440 --> 00:10:02,500
but God is alive and well in the churches

142
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:05,230
and is doing things in our midst.

143
00:10:05,230 --> 00:10:09,970
And he may be doing new things to reach this generation.

144
00:10:12,820 --> 00:10:14,260
I don't know anything about basketball.

145
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:17,200
I don't know anything about a bounce pass.

146
00:10:18,370 --> 00:10:20,170
And as a coach of your little ones,

147
00:10:20,250 --> 00:10:22,230
I've been reading that little manual every week

148
00:10:23,080 --> 00:10:24,280
What's the next drill?

149
00:10:24,860 --> 00:10:26,160
What's the next step?

150
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:30,520
And Marsha Wagner's team trounced my little team,

151
00:10:31,620 --> 00:10:36,270
but that's all right, because we're not keeping score.

152
00:10:37,960 --> 00:10:38,960
But let me tell you this.

153
00:10:40,280 --> 00:10:43,780
As a coach of these little ones in this outreach experience,

154
00:10:44,240 --> 00:10:50,070
to see those little kids come and to have them prayed for,

155
00:10:50,980 --> 00:10:53,520
and at the halftime of our practice in the games

156
00:10:53,520 --> 00:10:56,080
to hear the gospel message of Jesus Christ,

157
00:10:56,080 --> 00:10:59,620
and to have parents beginning to ask about the ministries of our church

158
00:10:59,620 --> 00:11:02,240
and beginning to feel a part of this community.

159
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:06,020
God does a new thing through sports to reach people

160
00:11:06,020 --> 00:11:08,780
and to love them and to bless them.

161
00:11:10,040 --> 00:11:12,960
And I find the great privilege to wear sneakers for Jesus

162
00:11:12,960 --> 00:11:16,040
and fumble around on a basketball court

163
00:11:16,040 --> 00:11:18,520
to share the message with families together.

164
00:11:18,880 --> 00:11:20,080
There's nothing greater than that.

165
00:11:21,300 --> 00:11:22,540
So what if we're at the margins?

166
00:11:22,620 --> 00:11:24,300
It's great to have families come.

167
00:11:24,300 --> 00:11:28,090
they may not know anything about this church

168
00:11:28,090 --> 00:11:30,790
or who God is or how much he loves them

169
00:11:30,790 --> 00:11:33,060
but we have a voice

170
00:11:33,060 --> 00:11:36,030
because God is alive and well and doing great things

171
00:11:36,030 --> 00:11:38,220
we're having a great time

172
00:11:38,220 --> 00:11:42,250
we may not be shaping policy at the government level

173
00:11:42,250 --> 00:11:44,890
but our young people are encountering God

174
00:11:44,890 --> 00:11:46,210
in their culture

175
00:11:46,210 --> 00:11:49,460
talk to our young people coming back from camp

176
00:11:49,460 --> 00:11:51,520
talk to their vim and their vigor

177
00:11:51,520 --> 00:11:54,580
for proclaiming the truth on the campuses today

178
00:11:54,580 --> 00:11:57,120
they're fired up

179
00:11:57,120 --> 00:11:58,540
That's why we prayed for them this morning.

180
00:11:58,600 --> 00:12:03,090
We don't want that fire to diminish because they're ready to be witnesses.

181
00:12:05,180 --> 00:12:07,140
We may not have the largest church around,

182
00:12:07,400 --> 00:12:12,760
but in our classes our people are definitely learning how to live like disciples of Jesus Christ.

183
00:12:14,220 --> 00:12:19,600
The church may be at the margins today, but God is definitely working from the margins.

184
00:12:20,670 --> 00:12:22,890
So let us not worry about being at the center.

185
00:12:22,890 --> 00:12:26,650
Let us minister from the outside like the first church did.

186
00:12:28,090 --> 00:12:28,810
And the church grew.

187
00:12:29,840 --> 00:12:30,580
Oh, did it grow.

188
00:12:32,890 --> 00:12:38,880
We're going to be faithful to live kingdom ethics, kingdom lifestyle, and kingdom priorities,

189
00:12:39,040 --> 00:12:40,740
whether from the center or the extremes.

190
00:12:41,880 --> 00:12:47,320
We're going to live out our mission statement that we worked with and finally put into this language.

191
00:12:47,320 --> 00:12:54,360
It's the same basic principles that 110 years ago a church was formed here, built on these same premises.

192
00:12:55,060 --> 00:12:57,300
We've just updated the language, and here they are.

193
00:12:57,980 --> 00:13:00,100
FFBC, Fullerton First Baptist Church,

194
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:04,580
is about celebrating God, loving others,

195
00:13:05,960 --> 00:13:07,620
reaching beyond our own,

196
00:13:09,100 --> 00:13:11,180
mentoring lives in His Spirit,

197
00:13:12,410 --> 00:13:14,470
and living the lives for which we were made.

198
00:13:15,540 --> 00:13:16,320
That's what we're about.

199
00:13:16,820 --> 00:13:19,680
It's what the New Testament has called the church to be about.

200
00:13:19,900 --> 00:13:22,360
It's about worship and community and outreach

201
00:13:22,360 --> 00:13:24,840
and discipleship and ministry to each other

202
00:13:24,840 --> 00:13:26,660
through our spiritual gifts.

203
00:13:26,660 --> 00:13:33,030
we're going to be faithful, even at the edge.

204
00:13:35,260 --> 00:13:39,460
I want to share our letterhead for a moment. You'll see it in the background.

205
00:13:39,580 --> 00:13:44,810
Here it comes to the foreground. What is that thing? Some of you wonder

206
00:13:44,810 --> 00:13:49,150
what that is. It's a compass. It's a compass

207
00:13:49,150 --> 00:13:53,880
with Jesus' cross at the bottom pointing

208
00:13:53,880 --> 00:13:58,890
north. It's what we're focused on. And in

209
00:13:58,890 --> 00:14:02,750
this day, we're charting new territory. Why do we have that as a sub-theme?

210
00:14:03,490 --> 00:14:04,370
What does that mean?

211
00:14:05,540 --> 00:14:12,260
We chart new territory because, friends, the church has never been in this particular situation ever.

212
00:14:12,780 --> 00:14:15,120
We're not only at the margins of the society.

213
00:14:15,360 --> 00:14:22,960
The early church was there, but they were never there in a world of such global communication,

214
00:14:23,200 --> 00:14:25,920
such globalism, such multicultural experience.

215
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:32,080
We've never been in this kind of culture directly, and the church is charting new territory.

216
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:39,920
We are on unfamiliar ground, but we're going to be faithful to point to Jesus

217
00:14:39,920 --> 00:14:44,480
and chart our course on these crazy seas before us.

218
00:14:46,320 --> 00:14:49,120
It's been called the rolling seas of post-modernity.

219
00:14:49,220 --> 00:14:50,040
There is a big mouthful.

220
00:14:50,640 --> 00:14:51,420
Let me explain that.

221
00:14:51,520 --> 00:14:52,840
I've been talking a lot about that.

222
00:14:53,140 --> 00:14:55,240
What is this post-modern thing?

223
00:14:55,380 --> 00:15:00,300
Why is that such a hip word in academia now trickling down into main culture?

224
00:15:00,580 --> 00:15:02,400
Well, here's what post-modernity really is.

225
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:07,400
It's a reaction to pretty much all that we have known as we've grown up with.

226
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:09,820
You see, we're modern people.

227
00:15:09,960 --> 00:15:14,600
We talk about the modern age, the modern world, and the postmodern reacts against that.

228
00:15:15,490 --> 00:15:17,930
Because absolute truth is now questioned.

229
00:15:19,270 --> 00:15:20,470
Is there such a thing?

230
00:15:21,910 --> 00:15:23,890
And if there is, can you really know it?

231
00:15:26,250 --> 00:15:29,530
The individual now decides right and wrong.

232
00:15:31,290 --> 00:15:34,030
Because in reality, there is no right and wrong.

233
00:15:34,170 --> 00:15:35,070
There's no truth.

234
00:15:35,070 --> 00:15:47,610
therefore whatever you want to do is okay if it works for you our culture rejects science

235
00:15:47,610 --> 00:15:57,300
and reason as the only path to knowledge they're more spiritual now actually and we see a rise

236
00:15:57,300 --> 00:16:05,620
of neo-pagan religion and if you question this talk to your children and grandchildren about

237
00:16:05,620 --> 00:16:10,300
what's happening on the campuses today wiccan covens are popping up all over the place

238
00:16:11,160 --> 00:16:14,280
Witchcraft is now part of the normative part of our society.

239
00:16:16,370 --> 00:16:19,430
We are in postmodern, unfamiliar water,

240
00:16:19,550 --> 00:16:22,130
and the church is charting new territory

241
00:16:22,130 --> 00:16:27,630
as we bring the gospel to this squishy, wobbly, unstable time.

242
00:16:28,700 --> 00:16:33,110
A time of constant change and discontinuous change.

243
00:16:34,560 --> 00:16:35,560
You see, in the old world,

244
00:16:37,120 --> 00:16:42,050
you could plan because change went incrementally in the same direction.

245
00:16:43,300 --> 00:16:45,180
And now it's discontinuous.

246
